{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_2892eb8f1ffepuxo9lrU3okPYc","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d76d147a1001qFhLBi9tvYTTF8","parts":[{"id":"prt_d76d15e09001Hzp4KBcIgtu0Gh","messageID":"msg_d76d147a1001qFhLBi9tvYTTF8","sessionID":"ses_2892eb8f1ffepuxo9lrU3okPYc","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_5e700ce9b5b2447b88cfb3c1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: \n2: ![](https://apiflask.com/_assets/apiflask-logo.png)\n3: \n4: # APIFlask\n5: \n6: [![Build status](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/actions/workflows/tests.yml/badge.svg)](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/actions) [![codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/apiflask/apiflask/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=2CFPCZ1DMY)](https://codecov.io/gh/apiflask/apiflask)\n7: \n8: APIFlask is a lightweight Python web API framework based on [Flask](https://github.com/pallets/flask). It's easy to use, highly customizable, ORM/ODM-agnostic, and 100% compatible with the Flask ecosystem.\n9: \n10: APIFlask supports both [marshmallow](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow) schemas and [Pydantic](https://docs.pydantic.dev/) models through a pluggable schema adapter system, giving you the flexibility to choose the validation approach that best fits your project.\n11: \n12: With APIFlask, you will have:\n13: \n14: - More sugars for view function (`@app.input()`, `@app.output()`, `@app.get()`, `@app.post()` and more)\n15: - Automatic request validation and deserialization\n16: - Automatic response formatting and serialization\n17: - Automatic [OpenAPI Specification](https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification) (OAS, formerly Swagger Specification) document generation\n18: - Automatic interactive API documentation\n19: - API authentication support (with [Flask-HTTPAuth](https://github.com/miguelgrinberg/flask-httpauth))\n20: - Automatic JSON response for HTTP errors\n21: \n22: \n23: ## Requirements\n24: \n25: - Python 3.9+\n26: - Flask 2.1+\n27: \n28: \n29: ## Installation\n30: \n31: For Linux and macOS:\n32: \n33: ```bash\n34: $ pip3 install apiflask\n35: ```\n36: \n37: For Windows:\n38: \n39: ```bash\n40: > pip install apiflask\n41: ```\n42: \n43: \n44: ## Links\n45: \n46: - Website: <https://apiflask.com>\n47: - Documentation: <https://apiflask.com/docs>\n48: - 中文文档: <https://zh.apiflask.com/docs>\n49: - PyPI Releases: <https://pypi.python.org/pypi/APIFlask>\n50: - Change Log: <https://apiflask.com/changelog>\n51: - Source Code: <https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask>\n52: - Issue Tracker: <https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/issues>\n53: - Discussion: <https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/discussions>\n54: - 中文论坛: <https://codekitchen.community>\n55: - Twitter: <https://twitter.com/apiflask>\n56: - Open Collective: <https://opencollective.com/apiflask>\n57: \n58: \n59: ## Donate\n60: \n61: If you find APIFlask useful, please consider [donating](https://opencollective.com/apiflask) today. Your donation keeps APIFlask maintained and evolving.\n62: \n63: Thank you to all our backers and sponsors!\n64: \n65: ### Backers\n66: \n67: [![](https://opencollective.com/apiflask/backers.svg?width=890)](https://opencollective.com/apiflask)\n68: \n69: ### Sponsors\n70: \n71: [![](https://opencollective.com/apiflask/sponsors.svg?width=890)](https://opencollective.com/apiflask)\n72: \n73: ## Example\n74: \n75: ```python\n76: from apiflask import APIFlask, Schema, abort\n77: from apiflask.fields import Integer, String\n78: from apiflask.validators import Length, OneOf\n79: \n80: app = APIFlask(__name__)\n81: \n82: pets = [\n83:     {'id': 0, 'name': 'Kitty', 'category': 'cat'},\n84:     {'id': 1, 'name': 'Coco', 'category': 'dog'}\n85: ]\n86: \n87: \n88: class PetIn(Schema):\n89:     name = String(required=True, validate=Length(0, 10))\n90:     category = String(required=True, validate=OneOf(['dog', 'cat']))\n91: \n92: \n93: class PetOut(Schema):\n94:     id = Integer()\n95:     name = String()\n96:     category = String()\n97: \n98: \n99: @app.get('/')\n100: def say_hello():\n101:     # returning a dict or list equals to use jsonify()\n102:     return {'message': 'Hello!'}\n103: \n104: \n105: @app.get('/pets/<int:pet_id>')\n106: @app.output(PetOut)\n107: def get_pet(pet_id):\n108:     if pet_id > len(pets) - 1:\n109:         abort(404)\n110:     # you can also return an ORM/ODM model class instance directly\n111:     # APIFlask will serialize the object into JSON format\n112:     return pets[pet_id]\n113: \n114: \n115: @app.patch('/pets/<int:pet_id>')\n116: @app.input(PetIn(partial=True))  # -> json_data\n117: @app.output(PetOut)\n118: def update_pet(pet_id, json_data):\n119:     # the validated and parsed input data will\n120:     # be injected into the view function as a dict\n121:     if pet_id > len(pets) - 1:\n122:         abort(404)\n123:     for attr, value in json_data.items():\n124:         pets[pet_id][attr] = value\n125:     return pets[pet_id]\n126: ```\n127: \n128: <details>\n129: <summary>You can use Pydantic models for type-hint based validation</summary>\n130: \n131: ```python\n132: from enum import Enum\n133: \n134: from apiflask import APIFlask, abort\n135: from pydantic import BaseModel, Field\n136: \n137: app = APIFlask(__name__)\n138: \n139: \n140: class PetCategory(str, Enum):\n141:     DOG = 'dog'\n142:     CAT = 'cat'\n143: \n144: \n145: class PetOut(BaseModel):\n146:     id: int\n147:     name: str\n148:     category: PetCategory\n149: \n150: \n151: class PetIn(BaseModel):\n152:     name: str = Field(min_length=1, max_length=50)\n153:     category: PetCategory\n154: \n155: \n156: pets = [\n157:     {'id': 0, 'name': 'Kitty', 'category': 'cat'},\n158:     {'id': 1, 'name': 'Coco', 'category': 'dog'}\n159: ]\n160: \n161: \n162: @app.get('/')\n163: def say_hello():\n164:     return {'message': 'Hello, Pydantic!'}\n165: \n166: \n167: @app.get('/pets')\n168: @app.output(list[PetOut])\n169: def get_pets():\n170:     return pets\n171: \n172: \n173: @app.get('/pets/<int:pet_id>')\n174: @app.output(PetOut)\n175: def get_pet(pet_id: int):\n176:     if pet_id > len(pets) or pet_id < 1:\n177:         abort(404)\n178:     return pets[pet_id - 1]\n179: \n180: \n181: @app.post('/pets')\n182: @app.input(PetIn, location='json')\n183: @app.output(PetOut, status_code=201)\n184: def create_pet(json_data: PetIn):\n185:     # the validated and parsed input data will\n186:     # be injected into the view function as a Pydantic model instance\n187:     new_id = len(pets) + 1\n188:     new_pet = PetOut(id=new_id, name=json_data.name, category=json_data.category)\n189:     pets.append(new_pet)\n190:     return new_pet\n191: ```\n192: \n193: </details>\n194: \n195: <details>\n196: <summary>Or use <code>async def</code></summary>\n197: \n198: ```bash\n199: $ pip install -U \"apiflask[async]\"\n200: ```\n201: \n202: ```python\n203: import asyncio\n204: \n205: from apiflask import APIFlask\n206: \n207: app = APIFlask(__name__)\n208: \n209: \n210: @app.get('/')\n211: async def say_hello():\n212:     await asyncio.sleep(1)\n213:     return {'message': 'Hello!'}\n214: ```\n215: \n216: See <em><a href=\"https://flask.palletsprojects.com/async-await\">Using async and await</a></em> for the details of the async support in Flask 2.0.\n217: \n218: </details>\n219: \n220: Save this as `app.py`, then run it with:\n221: \n222: ```bash\n223: $ flask run --debug\n224: ```\n225: \n226: Now visit the interactive API documentation (Swagger UI) at <http://localhost:5000/docs>:\n227: \n228: ![](https://apiflask.com/_assets/swagger-ui.png)\n229: \n230: Or you can change the API documentation UI when creating the APIFlask instance with the `docs_ui` parameter:\n231: \n232: ```py\n233: app = APIFlask(__name__, docs_ui='redoc')\n234: ```\n235: \n236: Now <http://localhost:5000/docs> will render the API documentation with Redoc.\n237: \n238: Supported `docs_ui` values (UI libraries) include:\n239: \n240: - `swagger-ui` (default value): [Swagger UI](https://github.com/swagger-api/swagger-ui)\n241: - `redoc`: [Redoc](https://github.com/Redocly/redoc)\n242: - `elements`: [Elements](https://github.com/stoplightio/elements)\n243: - `rapidoc`: [RapiDoc](https://github.com/rapi-doc/RapiDoc)\n244: - `rapipdf`: [RapiPDF](https://github.com/mrin9/RapiPdf)\n245: \n246: The auto-generated OpenAPI spec file is available at <http://localhost:5000/openapi.json>. You can also get the spec with [the `flask spec` command](https://apiflask.com/openapi/#the-flask-spec-command):\n247: \n248: ```bash\n249: $ flask spec\n250: ```\n251: \n252: For some complete examples, see [/examples](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/tree/main/examples).\n253: \n254: \n255: ## Relationship with Flask\n256: \n257: APIFlask is a thin wrapper on top of Flask. You only need to remember the following differences (see *[Migrating from Flask](https://apiflask.com/migrations/flask/)* for more details):\n258: \n259: - When creating an application instance, use `APIFlask` instead of `Flask`.\n260: - When creating a blueprint instance, use `APIBlueprint` instead of `Blueprint`.\n261: - The `abort()` function from APIFlask (`apiflask.abort`) returns JSON error response.\n262: \n263: For a minimal Flask application:\n264: \n265: ```python\n266: from flask import Flask, request\n267: from markupsafe import escape\n268: \n269: app = Flask(__name__)\n270: \n271: @app.route('/')\n272: def hello():\n273:     name = request.args.get('name', 'Human')\n274:     return f'Hello, {escape(name)}'\n275: ```\n276: \n277: Now change to APIFlask:\n278: \n279: ```python\n280: from apiflask import APIFlask  # step one\n281: from flask import request\n282: from markupsafe import escape\n283: \n284: app = APIFlask(__name__)  # step two\n285: \n286: @app.route('/')\n287: def hello():\n288:     name = request.args.get('name', 'Human')\n289:     return f'Hello, {escape(name)}'\n290: ```\n291: \n292: In a word, to make Web API development in Flask more easily, APIFlask provides `APIFlask` and `APIBlueprint` to extend Flask's `Flask` and `Blueprint` objects and it also ships with some helpful utilities. Other than that, you are actually using Flask.\n293: \n294: \n295: ## Credits\n296: \n297: APIFlask starts as a fork of [APIFairy](https://github.com/miguelgrinberg/APIFairy) and is inspired by [flask-smorest](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/flask-smorest) and [FastAPI](https://github.com/tiangolo/fastapi) (see *[Comparison and Motivations](https://apiflask.com/comparison)* for the comparison between these projects).\n\n(End of file - total 297 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\n![](https://apiflask.com/_assets/apiflask-logo.png)\n\n# APIFlask\n\n[![Build status](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/actions/workflows/tests.yml/badge.svg)](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/actions) [![codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/apiflask/apiflask/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=2CFPCZ1DMY)](https://codecov.io/gh/apiflask/apiflask)\n\nAPIFlask is a lightweight Python web API framework based on [Flask](https://github.com/pallets/flask). It's easy to use, highly customizable, ORM/ODM-agnostic, and 100% compatible with the Flask ecosystem.\n\nAPIFlask supports both [marshmallow](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow) schemas and [Pydantic](https://docs.pydantic.dev/) models through a pluggable schema adapter system, giving you the flexibility to choose the validation approach that best fits your project.\n\nWith APIFlask, you will have:\n\n- More sugars for view function (`@app.input()`, `@app.output()`, `@app.get()`, `@app.post()` and more)\n- Automatic request validation and deserialization\n- Automatic response formatting and serialization\n- Automatic [OpenAPI Specification](https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification) (OAS, formerly Swagger Specification) document generation\n- Automatic interactive API documentation\n- API authentication support (with [Flask-HTTPAuth](https://github.com/miguelgrinberg/flask-httpauth))\n- Automatic JSON response for HTTP errors","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.md","time":{"start":1775814926278,"end":1775814926289}}}]}
